  "prompt": "How do semiconductors differ from conductors and insulators?",
  "response": "Semiconductors differ from conductors and insulators in several key ways:\n\n1. Electrical Conductivity\n- Conductors: High electrical conductivity\n- Semiconductors: Intermediate conductivity\n- Insulators: Very low electrical conductivity\n\n2. Energy Band Structure\n- Conductors: Overlapping valence and conduction bands\n- Semiconductors: Small energy gap between valence and conduction bands\n- Insulators: Large energy gap between valence and conduction bands\n\n3. Temperature Effects\n- Conductors: Conductivity decreases with increasing temperature\n- Semiconductors: Conductivity increases with temperature\n- Insulators: Minimal conductivity change with temperature\n\n4. Electron Movement\n- Conductors: Free electrons easily move\n- Semiconductors: Electrons can be excited across small energy gap\n- Insulators: Electrons cannot easily move between bands\n\n5. Typical Materials\n- Conductors: Metals like copper, silver\n- Semiconductors: Silicon, germanium\n- Insulators: Glass, rubber, ceramic\n\n6. Doping Capability\n- Conductors: Cannot be easily doped\n- Semiconductors: Can be doped to modify electrical properties\n- Insulators: Generally cannot be doped\n\nThese differences make semiconductors unique and crucial in electronic device manufacturing.",
